mydata_dob2 <- mydata_dob %>%
  select(IDNUMBER, GENDER, GROUP, L1dob, L1age, L1dot,
         L2dob, L2age, L2dot, L3dob, L3age, L3dot) %>%
  mutate_at(c(4, 6, 7, 9, 10, 12), as.character) %>%
  rename(ID2 = IDNUMBER, L1_dob = L1dob, L1_age = L1age, L1_dot = L1dot,
         L2_dob = L2dob, L2_age = L2age, L2_dot = L2dot, L3_dob = L3dob, L3_age = L3age, L3_dot = L3dot)

mydata_merged <- left_join(mydata_wide, mydata_dob2)
## Joining, by = "ID2"
wide_to_long2 <- mydata_merged %>%
  gather(-ID2, -GENDER, -GROUP, key = "timepoint", value = "value") %>%
  separate(timepoint, into = c("Omit", "Timepoint", "Omit2", "Variable"), sep = c(1,2, 3)) %>%
  select(-Omit, -Omit2) %>%
  spread(key = Variable, value = value) %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  mutate(dob = mdy(dob), dot = mdy(dot))

The fixed effects estimate for the intercept is greater than it was previously (40.32 vs.Â 38.72) and the residual variance is smaller (40.32 vs.Â 52.95). This makes sense; as we add IVs to our model, we would expect to be able to account for more variance. ___

Adding a random slope slightly decreases the average intercept (40.10 vs.Â 40.32), increases the average slope (2.05 vs.Â 1.86), and reduces residual variance (37.38 vs.Â 40.32). I think itâs worthwhile keeping the random slope because total variance attributable to fixed and random effects, as evaluated by pseudo R2, increases roughly 6%.
___

Item 5: Interpret the correlation between the slope and the intercept.

The fixed effects correlation = .36. This suggests a medium-sized relationship between the average intercept and the average slope wherein greater intercepts (i.e., more words correct) are associated with steeper slopes (i.e., faster rate of improvement in words correct). However, this association is not so large so as to be redundant. The random effects correlation (r = .45) models the relationship between intercept and slope on the individual level, designating the correlation between an individualâs deviation from the average intercept and their deviation from the average slope.
